# Professional Backend Restructure Walkthrough

I have successfully separated the backend logic from the mobile application frontend and organized it into a professional, scalable structure at the root of your project.

## Changes Overview

### 1. New Standalone Backend (`backend/`)
The backend is built with **FastAPI** and follows a standard enterprise architecture:
- **`app/models/`**: Pydantic schemas for data validation (Inspections, Service Requests).
- **`app/services/`**: Data persistence layer with a centralized mock database.
- **`app/controllers/`**: Business logic layer that coordinates service calls.
- **`app/api/v1/endpoints/`**: RESTful API routes (`/inspections`, `/service-requests`).
- **[main.py](file:///f:/DigiQC/backend/app/main.py)**: The main entry point with CORS enabled for mobile connectivity.

### 2. Mobile App Integration (`DigiQC-mobile/`)
- All local mock data in the UI has been removed.
- **Services**: Updated [inspection.service.ts](file:///f:/DigiQC/DigiQC-mobile/services/inspection.service.ts) and [service-request.service.ts](file:///f:/DigiQC/DigiQC-mobile/services/service-request.service.ts) to use `fetch()` to communicate with the local backend.
- **UI Components**: Refactored all main screens ([Inspections](file:///f:/DigiQC/DigiQC-mobile/app/inspections.tsx#18-28), [Reports](file:///f:/DigiQC/DigiQC-mobile/services/inspection.service.ts#19-23), [Service](file:///f:/DigiQC/DigiQC-mobile/app/service.tsx#9-10), `Checklists`, `Start Inspection`) to handle asynchronous data loading with loading indicators.
- **Constants**: Centralized UI styling tokens into [constants/status-config.ts](file:///f:/DigiQC/DigiQC-mobile/constants/status-config.ts).

## How to Run the Project

### Phase 1: Start the Backend
1. Open a terminal in the root `f:\DigiQC` directory.
2. Activate your virtual environment: [.\venv\Scripts\activate](file:///f:/DigiQC/venv/Scripts/activate)
3. Install dependencies: `pip install -r backend/requirements.txt`
4. Run the server: `python backend/run.py`
   - The API will be available at `http://localhost:8000`.
   - You can view the automatic API documentation at `http://localhost:8000/docs`.

### Phase 2: Start the Mobile App
1. Open another terminal in `f:\DigiQC\DigiQC-mobile`.
2. Run `npx expo start`.
3. The app will now fetch data live from your new Python backend!

